Statistical analyses

Wild, urban population

For each bird, calculated the condition as a regression of mass and tarsus length, using the following formula: Condit<-lm(Mass~Tarsus)

Because some wild birds were recaptures and sampled more than once, I then used a random number generator in R to create a random ID and select one data point, randomly, from birds with more than one data point during the study. This then changed the sample size between the weeks. The table below shows the week # (first row) with sample size below.

## 
##  0  1  2  3  4  5  6  7  8 
## 14 16 23 18 15 21 19 17 18
## Loading required package: plyr

The below graphs show the trend of body condition in the wild-caught birds over the course of the study.

## Warning: Removed 30 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

A type-II ANOVA, using unique bird IDs only (no recapture data included), shows a significant effect of week on body condition, but not feeder status. Additionally, there is no significant interaction between feeder status and week, suggesting the effect is of time, but not the feeder treatment “cycle” number.

Using likelihood tests of mixed models, time (cycle number 1 or 2) significantly affects body condition, compared to the reduced null model. However, incorporating feeder status as a fixed effect does not significantly increase likelihood. Additionally, no interaction between feeder status and time is significant.

Next are plots of coccidia occurence in the wild,urban population across the study. Coccidia was collected from fecal samples and was scored from 0 - 4.

{r, echo=FALSE} # Anova(lm(Coccidia ~ FeederStatus*Week, data = uniqWild)) # Anova(lmer(Coccidia ~ FeederStatus*Week + (1|ID), data=fwild)) #

Using model likelihood ratio test, cycle number (time) showed a trend towards affecting coccidia load, however, this was not significant. Feeder status did not significantly affect coccidia load, and there was no significant interaction between feeder status and cycle number.
